Summary of notation 
 
 

Vacuum     Choice 
Several vacuum  choices have been  proposed in the literature,  and we
discuss some of  them in the Appendix. Here we  shall pursue however a
different approach.  Instead of declaring one of the several different
vacua to  be the correct one,  we shall abstract the  property all the
different vacua share and use  that property to define a general class
of "sensible" vacuum states.

Specifying  a  set of  mode  functions    is tantamount  to
choosing a  vacuum state .  Because   is determined by
the equation of  motion (), all that has  to be done to
define a vacuum is to  specify initial conditions for .  We shall
require  of any  vacuum state  that in  the limit  where  the physical
length  of the  perturbation is  much smaller  than the  Hubble radius
(), the mode  functions approach  the ones  in Minkowski
space .  In fact, in  such a limit
cosmic expansion should be irrelevant. In other words, when 
 the values  of  and its time  derivative respectively approach
(up to an irrelevant phase)
 
All the vacuum choices we discuss in the appendix share this property.
However, in  an inflating universe (where   remains finite) physics
is not  well defined in  the limit .  In that  limit the
physical  length of the  perturbation is  infinitely smaller  than the
Planck   length.   Hence,   one  cannot   rely  on   our  conventional
understanding  of  physics  in  that regime(In  Pre-Big  Bang
      and    Epkyrotic/Cyclic     scenarios,  the  universe contracts  from  Minkowski  space at  past
  infinity.  In that  case the limit   is physically well
  defined.  For  those models, the  ambiguities we are  considering in
  this work  can be avoided.) .  Thus,  for a given mode  , the best
one can  do is pick  a vacuum by  prescribing the values of   and
 at a finite time   such that the physical length of the
mode  is  much  smaller than  the  Hubble  radius  (in order  for  the
expansion  to be  "unimportant"), but  much larger  than  the Planck
scale  (in order for  trans-Planckian effects  to be  negligible).  We
shall take   to be  the time when  the physical length  of the
mode equals a given (fixed) length scale ,
 
The scale   is the highest possible scale  where we can trust
our  understanding  of physics.   Conventionally  it  is assumed  that
